There are really three different main types
of formula.

00:00:15.950 --> 00:00:19.391
And you're going to talk to your doctor figure
out which one is the right choice for you.

00:00:19.391 --> 00:00:21.480
But I'm going to quickly run through them
here.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:24.000
Okay, number one cow's milk formula.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:25.439
I've got some examples here.

00:00:25.439 --> 00:00:31.080
I have Similac and I have Enfamil.

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:34.100
You can also find lactose- free formulas.

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:38.730
Here's one that is a soy-based infant formula.

00:00:38.730 --> 00:00:42.620
And you can get lactose-free formula's that
are based on cow's milk.

00:00:42.620 --> 00:00:45.730
So talk to your doctor, figure out which one
you want to use.

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:51.870
When it comes to what type of formula, again,
three main types: powdered formula and then

00:00:51.870 --> 00:00:54.950
you can also get liquid formula or concentrated
liquid formula.

00:00:54.950 --> 00:00:58.949
Now most people I know use the powdered formula
for a couple reasons.

00:00:58.949 --> 00:01:03.829
Number one, it's very easy with powdered formula
to make smaller or larger quantities and not

00:01:03.829 --> 00:01:05.140
to waste it.

00:01:05.140 --> 00:01:09.960
It's also good storage wise because it doesn't
take up as much space and it does tend to

00:01:09.960 --> 00:01:11.050
be cheaper.

00:01:11.050 --> 00:01:14.270
However, if you're going on a long trip or
something like that and you don't think you're

00:01:14.270 --> 00:01:17.630
going to have access to water you might want
to consider one of the liquid formulas.

00:01:17.630 --> 00:01:19.600
It's sort of a nice option.

00:01:19.600 --> 00:01:26.299
So in terms of how to prepare and store powdered
formula, first make sure you use an iron fortified

00:01:26.299 --> 00:01:32.229
infant powdered formula per the recommendation
of the American Academy of Pediatrics during

00:01:32.229 --> 00:01:35.190
your baby's first year of life.

00:01:35.190 --> 00:01:38.490
Always check the expiration date on the formula
can.

00:01:38.490 --> 00:01:41.990
Formula can go bad and can be unsafe for your
baby.

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:44.929
Once a can is open it's good for one month.

00:01:44.929 --> 00:01:50.590
Lastly, formula actually has a very short
shelf life after the powders mixed with water.

00:01:50.590 --> 00:01:56.130
So do not leave powdered mix formula at room
temperature for more than one hour and always

00:01:56.130 --> 00:01:58.600
throw out what your child does not drink.

00:01:58.600 --> 00:02:01.509
Good reason to not make more than you need.

00:02:01.509 --> 00:02:06.729
Once you mix the powder with water, it will
keep for up to 48 hours in a refrigerator.

00:02:06.729 --> 00:02:11.319
Okay, now can I use tap water in making formula?

00:02:11.319 --> 00:02:13.630
This is something on which you should check
with your doctor.

00:02:13.630 --> 00:02:18.030
I did talk to my doctor about this and he
said in New York City it's fine.

00:02:18.030 --> 00:02:22.400
But you have to make sure because in some
cases actually fluoride levels can be too

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:27.030
high and doctor's will want you to alternate
between using tap water and using other types

00:02:27.030 --> 00:02:28.030
of water.

00:02:28.030 --> 00:02:29.350
So this is something you should check out.

